post_text:
2019-2020 high school yearbooks go home tomorrow during materials pick-up day! Have you purchased yours yet?

Not sure if you already purchased a book? If you haven't yet purchased a book, instead of a yearbook in your materials box tomorrow, you'll get a slip of paper with ordering instructions and will be able to purchase one in the office for $45.

Class of 2020: If you would like your yearbook to go home with a returning middle or high school student, please let Ms. Frey (jamie.frey@stpaul.k12.or.us) know before 8:00am on Wednesday. Otherwise, you will be able to pick up your copy in the high school office.

post_text:
Important Update on St. Paul District Operations

March 17, 2020

Dear St Paul Community,

These are unprecedented times in our district and you may have heard that our schools must now be closed until April 28th by virtue of an order from our governor. It is my goal this week and as soon as practicable following spring break to develop a plan that will provide online and packet learning opportunities for students through April 28th. Please know that our dedicated staff is doing everything they can to develop an instructional program that will serve students online and with packets. Please click on the link below or go to our website and fill out the internet access survey so that we can better assist you in supporting your childs' learning needs. I will update you as additional information becomes available. Please be safe and care for your family during this difficult time.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/T5RB5BJ

Sincerely

Joseph Wehrli
Superintendent/St Paul School District

post_text:
Important Update on St. Paul District Operations

March 16, 2020

Dear St Paul Community,

I hope this message finds you and your family well and that you have been able to adjust your schedules to accommodate this unprecedented school closure situation.
-Our district buildings, including the batting cages, will remain closed to the public with only essential staff allowed to report. Though our track and other outside areas remain open to the public I would ask that all recommended social distancing practices be followed by those who choose to come walk or run on the track. Our buildings are being disinfected this week and we are delivering food boxes to some of our families in need of supplies. If you are in need or know of a family that can use the district support with food during this closure please contact the school at 503-633-2541 we will do everything we can to support our community during the closure.

Please keep watching our website for updates.

Sincerely,

Joseph M. Wehrli
St. Paul School District
Superintendent/Elementary Principal

post_text:
Community Survey

In Spring 2019, Oregon leaders passed HB 3427 known as the Student Success Act, which will increase revenue for K-12 schools. This winter, each Oregon school district will apply for funds from the Student Investment Account created by the Student Success Act. Applications will be available for funding in four key areas:

1. Increased instructional time
2. Student health and safety
3. Class size reduction
4. Well-rounded learning opportunities

This survey is one opportunity for you to share your priorities in the categories of investment allowed under the Student Success Act.

Click on a link below to participate in the survey.

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/SJMKZHQ (English)

https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/KWMFDSS (Spanish)

post_text:
December 6, 2019

Dear. St Paul Community,

Superintendent Wehrli continues to recover from his accident. On Wednesday, he had surgery on his hip and is already able to sit up in a chair. The next phase of his recovery will include transitioning to an inpatient rehabilitation facility and then hopefully home for the Holidays. Mr. Wehrli is very thankful for all the support the community has provided and looks forward to getting back to work.

Patrick Schrader
Principal
St. Paul Middle/High School

post_text:
St. Paul – Woodburn Independent Article February 13, 2019

One area school pitched a perfect game: St. Paul, achieved a 100 percent graduation rate in 2017-18, up from just over 92 percent the previous two years and 89 percent in 2014-15. District officials go into each year expecting nothing less.

"Our goal in St Paul is to graduate 100-percent of our students each year," St. Paul Superintendent Joe Wehrli said. "Our middle and high-school staff does an excellent job of monitoring each student's progress closely as they work toward graduation, and they provide additional support as necessary to give each student the opportunity to be academically successful.
"The St Paul School Board continues to set high expectations of success for both academic excellence and active involvement in activities from our students," Wehrli added. "Their expectations are coupled with a willingness to find ways to fund the programs necessary to support student success."

Joe Wehrli
Superintendent/ES Principal
St. Paul School District
20449 Main St. NE
St. Paul OR 97137
503-633-2541

The St. Paul Elementary Parent Teacher Club is very excited to announce that we are hosting the World-Famous Harlem Wizards in the St. Paul High School Gym on May 12th at 6 pm. The Wizards will play a team of local teachers, coaches, and community members!

This will be a family-friendly, affordable event - all right here in St. Paul!!

More information will be coming soon, including a link to purchase tickets online!

Feel free to pass this information on to your friends and family. Everyone is welcome!!

We hope to see you everyone there!

Here is a link to a short video about the Harlem Wizards.
